>
  <ServicePageLayout
    title="High Net Worth Divorce"
    headline="Maryland High Net Worth Divorce Attorneys"
    intro="When significant wealth is at stake, you need attorneys who can navigate complexity with precision. Our Maryland high net worth divorce team handles complex asset portfolios — investment accounts, real estate holdings, retirement assets, business interests, and more — with the strategic sophistication your case demands."
  >
    <h2>The High-Stakes World of High Net Worth Divorce</h2>
    <p>
      Divorce involving substantial assets requires a fundamentally different level of legal expertise than a standard divorce proceeding. The financial stakes are higher, the legal questions more complex, and the need for meticulous preparation and strategic thinking more critical than ever.
    </p>
    <p>
      At Child Custody with a Plan, our attorneys handle high net worth divorces throughout Maryland — including the most complex cases in <strong>Montgomery County</strong>, <strong>Baltimore City and County</strong>, <strong>Howard County</strong>, and <strong>Anne Arundel County</strong>. We have the expertise, the professional network, and the strategic depth to represent high-net-worth individuals effectively.
    </p>

    <h2>What Qualifies as a High Net Worth Divorce?</h2>
    <p>
      While there is no single dollar threshold, high net worth divorces typically involve one or more of the following characteristics:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Total marital estate valued at $1 million or more</li>
      <li>Multiple real estate properties (residential, commercial, investment)</li>
      <li>Significant investment and brokerage accounts</li>
      <li>Complex retirement assets (pensions, 401(k)s, IRAs, deferred compensation)</li>
      <li>Business interests or professional practice ownership</li>
      <li>Stock options, restricted stock units, and executive compensation</li>
      <li>Offshore accounts or international assets</li>
      <li>Art, collectibles, or significant personal property</li>
      <li>Trusts and complex estate planning structures</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Key Asset Categories We Handle</h2>

    <h3>Real Estate Holdings</h3>
    <p>
      Multiple property ownership adds significant complexity to Maryland divorce. Each property must be appraised at fair market value, its marital vs. separate character must be established, and a disposition strategy must be developed. We handle marital homes, investment properties, vacation homes, commercial real estate, and rental properties.
    </p>

    <h3>Investment & Retirement Accounts</h3>
    <p>
      Investment portfolios, brokerage accounts, IRAs, 401(k)s, 403(b)s, pensions, deferred compensation plans, and other retirement assets all require specialized handling. We work with financial planners and QDRO specialists to ensure these assets are divided accurately, efficiently, and in a way that minimizes adverse tax consequences.
    </p>

    <h3>Business Interests</h3>
    <p>
      Privately held businesses, professional practices, partnerships, and LLCs are among the most complex and contested assets in high net worth divorce. Our team works with certified business valuators to establish defensible valuations and develop creative solutions for division. Learn more on our <a href="/divorces-involving-businesses" class="text-teal-600 hover:underline">Divorces Involving Businesses</a> page.
    </p>

    <h3>Stock Options & Executive Compensation</h3>
    <p>
      Vested and unvested stock options, RSUs, performance bonuses, and long-term incentive plans must be carefully analyzed to determine what portion represents marital property. The timing of grants, vesting schedules, and exercise events all affect classification. Our attorneys have deep experience in this specialized area.
    </p>

    <h3>Trusts & Estate Planning Structures</h3>
    <p>
      When marital assets are held in trusts or complex estate planning vehicles, additional legal analysis is required to determine whether trust assets are accessible in divorce. We work with trust attorneys and estate planning specialists to ensure these structures are properly evaluated.
    </p>

    <h3>International & Offshore Assets</h3>
    <p>
      Offshore accounts, international real estate, and foreign business interests present unique challenges in Maryland divorce. We work with international legal specialists when necessary to ensure all assets are identified, disclosed, and properly addressed.
    </p>

    <h2>Hidden Asset Discovery</h2>
    <p>
      In high net worth divorces, the risk of asset concealment is real. Our attorneys are skilled at using discovery tools — interrogatories, depositions, subpoenas, and forensic accounting — to uncover hidden assets, undervalued businesses, undisclosed income, and fraudulent transfers. We leave no stone unturned.
    </p>

    <h2>Tax Implications in High Net Worth Divorce</h2>
    <p>
      Tax consequences can dramatically affect the real value of a divorce settlement. Capital gains taxes, ordinary income tax on retirement distributions, the basis step-up rules, and transfer tax considerations must all be factored into any equitable distribution strategy. We work with tax professionals to ensure settlements are structured tax-efficiently.
    </p>

    <h2>Our High Net Worth Divorce Team</h2>
    <p>
      Led by <strong>Josephia Rouse</strong> (2025 Elite Lawyer Award) and her team of skilled associates, Child Custody with a Plan brings a deep bench of legal talent to high net worth cases. Our attorneys apply the <strong>PROMISE Framework™</strong> at every stage — researching, organizing, and strategically mobilizing to achieve the best possible outcome.
    </p>

